{"questionId":"12516","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A sphere with diameter 3 474 000 metres can model the shape of the Moon.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use this model to calculate the circumference of the Moon in <strong>kilometres</strong>. Give your full calculator display.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p style=\"color:#999;font-size:90%;font-style:italic;\">* This question is from an exam for a previous syllabus, and may contain minor differences in marking or structure.</p><p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{3\\,474\\,000 \\times \\pi }}{{1000}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>474</mn>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>000</mn>\n      <mo>×</mo>\n      <mi>π</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1000</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct numerator and <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for dividing by 1000&nbsp;<strong>OR</strong> equivalent, such as <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{3\\,474\\,000 \\times 2 \\times \\pi }}{{2000}}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>474</mn>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>000</mn>\n      <mo>×</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mo>×</mo>\n      <mi>π</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>2000</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> ie diameter.<br>Do not accept use of area formula ie <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\pi {r^2}\">\n  <mi>π</mi>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>r</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p>10 913.89287… (km)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)&nbsp; (C3)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","meta":{"questionId":"12516","referenceCode":"19M.1.SL.TZ2.T_1a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Use this model to calculate the circumference of the Moon in kilometres. Give your full calculator display.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Prior learning","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.1—Using standard form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}